28c46d6f-a9e7-4fc5-9249-725c0241f01f.1e46aa95-de06-423a-a286-a20fc2fed9fc.description=
Service to perform HTTP POST using the Java HTTP Client. This  operation is used to execute an HTTP POST request while sending HTTP POST data in raw form instead of including it in the request itself.

Inputs\:
    url - The URL where to send the HTTP POST request.
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    kerberosConfFile - The  path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the "kdc" (Key Distribution Center) and "realm" get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. 
Valid values\: This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "timeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    socketTimeout - The time to wait for data to be retrieved, in milliseconds. 
Valid values\: This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
Default value\: 8080
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy server.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the "proxyUsername" input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    file - The file to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method. This should be a path to a file/document on the disk.
    string - The message body to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method.
    contentType - The content type that should be set in the request header, representing the MIME-type of the data in the message body.
Examples\: "text/html", "text/html; charset\=UTF-8", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded".
    characterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP POST request and response.
Default value\: UTF-8
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker(Man In The Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option.
Default value\: allow_all
Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "keystore" is empty, "keystorePassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, "trustPassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    headerNamesList - The list containing the header names to use for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - The list containing the header values to use for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - The list containing the names of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - The list containing the values of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separates list elements.
Default value\: ','

Results\: 
    returnCode - This is the primary output. A code used to determine the operation response, specifying whether the operation is successful or not.
    resultText - The raw result of the operation.
    document - The complete document returned by the Http Client Post Raw operation.
    URL - The URL used for the HTTP request.
    pageLoadTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken for the page to load.
    responseTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken before the server responded.
    errorMessage - An informational message that can help determine the cause of error, if an error occurred.
    httpResult - The description of the HTTP response returned by the web server for the request sent by this operation. This result contains the HTTP response status or GENERAL_ERROR if the HTTP request could not be executed.
Example\: SUCCESS, PAGE_NOT_FOUND, UNAUTHORIZED, FORBIDDEN and so on.
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by "delimiter".
    status - The HTTP response code.
Example\: HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    PAGE_NOT_FOUND - The URL specified to POST from was not found.
    INFORMATIONAL - The POST was not fully processed, the server responded with an informational response.
    REDIRECTION - The specified URL has moved.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../.cer -alias  -keystore /java/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
2. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
      -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
      -storepass ab987c -validity 180
It creates a certificate chain in a new keystore containing only one certificate.
3. If the value assigned to the "trustAllRoots" input is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
4. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled 'Advanced Features'. Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\=,CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the 'Properties' window and press the 'Attribute Editor' tab. Observe the values of the 'servicePrincipalName' attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, HTTP/\:port.
5. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, use the "queryNamesList" and "queryValuesList" inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the URL. For example, http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2. If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and the "url" inputs, the used value is the one from the "queryValuesList", not the one included in the "url".
6. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.
7. This operation uses chunked transfer encoding, which may cause failures when using HTTP servers and proxies that do not support HTTP/1.1 protocol.
28c46d6f-a9e7-4fc5-9249-725c0241f01f.2981b6c3-c425-4416-80b0-591880ee2789.description=
Checks to see if the specified file can be read from.
Depending on the Operating System, the operation will either check all file
permissions, or will check to see if the file is marked as readonly.

Input Parameters\:
source - file to check.

Responses\:
success -  if the file is readable
failure - if the file does not exist or cannot be read.
28c46d6f-a9e7-4fc5-9249-725c0241f01f.37991fb8-8c6c-4049-824b-d4ad5d76c8d3.description=
Insert an object into a JSON array, optionally specifying the position at which to insert the new object. 

This Operation differes from the 'Add to Array' operation in that this one will try and validate the new element as
a JSON object, whereas 'Add to Array' will just wrap the element in quotes and treat it as a string. This means 
that the element passed into this operation must be a valid JSON object, or the operation will fail. 

When specifying the index to an array element in javascript it is possible to use the standard notation, where the 1st 
element from the left is index 0, and the right-most element is (n-1), in an array with n elements. However, 
it is also possible to specify elements starting from the right side of the array using negative numbers, in which case
the right-most element is referred to by index -1 and the left-most element is at position (-1 * n), again for an array with n elements.

Inputs\:
    array - String representation of a JSON array. Arrays in JSON are comma seperated lists of objects, enclosed in square brackets ( [ ] ).
Examples\: [1,2,3] or ["one","two","three"] or [{"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, 3, "four"]

    element - The element to insert into the array. As noted above, this must be a valid JSON object or the operation will fail. It can be 
                    any valid JSON object; such as a number, string, an array, or a name/value pair list. Numbers can be entered as-is, strings
                    must be wrapped in quotes, and objects must be formated correctly (see examples below for more info)
Valid values\: Any valid JSON object
Examples\: 1 or "a string" or {"one"\:"two", "three"\:"four"} or [1,2,3]

    index -The index in the array at which to insert the new element. If index is undefined, or index is equal to the length of the array 
               (one past the last element), the new element is placed at the end of the array. See the notes above for more information
               on using negative numbers to specify array elements.
               If the index is valid, the new element is inserted at that position, and all remaining elements are shifted one position to the right.

Valid values\: Integer between (-1*n) and (n-1) for an array with n elements.
Default value\: undefined (insert the new element at the end of the array)


Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation failed. See the message in returnResult for details


Results\:
    returnResult - The new JSON array with the inserted element.
28c46d6f-a9e7-4fc5-9249-725c0241f01f.6c9e0565-b3d6-49ce-94a9-f86d87bbafae.description=
This operation is used to retrieve a value from a list. When the index of an element from a list is known, this operation can be used to extract the element.

Inputs\:
    list - A list to get the value from.
    delimiter - The delimiter that separates values in the list.
Default value\: ','
    index - The index of the value (starting at 0) to retrieve from the list.
Valid values\: an integer, end (for the last element), end-1 (for the second to last element)

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value found at the specified index in the list, if the value specified for the "index" input field is positive and less than the size of the list. Otherwise, it contains the value specified for "index".

Responses\:
     success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
     failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

28c46d6f-a9e7-4fc5-9249-725c0241f01f.90652c3a-d92c-4935-88e4-b6eae563d313.description=
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter - The string to filter on (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    iterate - Determines whether the content of the file should be iterated or not. If set to "true", the content of the file will be iterated row by row and for each subsequent call, the next row will be returned. If set to "false", the content of the file will not be iterated and only the number of lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values\: true, false
    delimiter – If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    eofReset - If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    count - The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of rows available for retrieval from the source file.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - The operation successfully read the file (if iterate is true, more rows are available).
    no more items - No more items are available for retrieval (if iterate is set to true).
    failure - The operation failed to read the file.

Notes\:
1. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
2. Note that the "filter" match is not performed based on a regular expression, although the filter field may contain one. The operation only checks for each row if it contains the string given as filter. 
3. If i"terate" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "iterate" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.
5. If the value provided in the "delimiter" field is not null, the entire file will be read once and returned regardless of the value of the "iterate" field.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the delimiter input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will be blank and the count output field will contain the value 4 (representing the number of lines in the file).
